The number of antennal and uropodal articles in addition to pereopodal setation varies between individuals. In spite of the absence of the illustration of the cheliped in the original description (
Brum, 1973
) and the lack of cheliped in the type material we examined, the author stated that this appendix lacks an exopod. This statement was not confirmed through the examination of our material.
Brum ( 1973 )
also described the rostrum of P. c a r i n a t u s as having a short tiny mesial spine. However, the species has a truncate rostrum and what can be observed in a dorsal view is the apex of the epistoma. Indeed, the epistoma was also named, in a wrong way, of pseudorostrum (
Brum, 1973
) and conic clypeus (
Brum, 1974
).
